📄 PROJECT DOCUMENT
Enterprise Multi-Floor Networking Design (Third Networking Project)
1. Overview

This project presents the design and implementation of a scalable enterprise campus network for a multi-department organization operating across three floors of a building.

The network was designed using Cisco Packet Tracer and follows a hierarchical architecture with redundant routing, VLAN segmentation, wireless access, and centralized server services.

The aim is to provide secure, reliable, and efficient communication between all departments while ensuring future scalability.

2. Network Requirements Summary

The organization consists of multiple departments distributed across three floors:

Floor 1
Reception → 192.168.8.0/24
Store → 192.168.7.0/24
Logistics → 192.168.6.0/24
Floor 2
Finance → 192.168.5.0/24
Human Resources → 192.168.4.0/24
Sales → 192.168.3.0/24
Floor 3
Administration → 192.168.2.0/24
IT Department → 192.168.1.0/24 (DHCP + Server services)
3. Network Architecture Design

The network uses a three-router redundant topology (triangle design):

Core Routing Layer
RF1
RF2
RF3

The routers are interconnected using serial links:

10.10.10.0/30
10.10.10.4/30
10.10.10.8/30

This design ensures:

Redundancy
Fault tolerance
Multiple routing paths
4. VLAN and Subnet Design

Each department is assigned its own VLAN and subnet to ensure isolation and security.

Department	Network
IT	192.168.1.0/24
Admin	192.168.2.0/24
Sales	192.168.3.0/24
HR	192.168.4.0/24
Finance	192.168.5.0/24
Logistics	192.168.6.0/24
Store	192.168.7.0/24
Reception	192.168.8.0/24

Each VLAN operates independently while inter-VLAN communication is enabled via routing.

5. Key Technologies Implemented
Network Design
Hierarchical campus architecture
Multi-router redundant topology
VLAN-based segmentation
Routing
Static routing / dynamic routing between routers
Redundant triangular router design
Services
DHCP server (located in IT department)
Centralized IP allocation
Wireless
Access points deployed per department
Full wireless coverage per floor
Switching
VLAN configuration on access switches
Department-based segmentation
6. IP Addressing Strategy
Private IPv4 addressing scheme used (192.168.0.0 – 192.168.8.0 range)
Each department has a /24 subnet for scalability
Router interconnection uses /30 point-to-point links (10.10.10.0 series)
7. Server Infrastructure

The IT department hosts:

DHCP Server
Central network services
Management systems

All other departments obtain IP addresses dynamically via DHCP.

8. Network Features

✔ Multi-router redundancy
✔ VLAN-based segmentation
✔ Wireless connectivity in all departments
✔ Centralized DHCP
✔ Scalable IP addressing scheme
✔ Fault-tolerant routing topology
✔ Inter-department communication

9. Testing and Verification

The following tests were successful:

Same VLAN communication
Inter-VLAN routing
DHCP IP assignment
Router connectivity (RF1, RF2, RF3)
End-to-end connectivity
Wireless device connectivity
Server reachability (IT department)
10. Conclusion

The designed network successfully meets the requirements of a scalable enterprise campus environment. The implementation ensures redundancy, efficient routing, and proper segmentation of departments using VLANs and subnetting.

The architecture is suitable for future expansion and additional services.
